&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Applying pressure and reducing temperature&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Liquefaction of gases is primarily achieved by &lt;strong&gt;applying pressure and reducing temperature&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This process involves compressing the gas to a point where it can be cooled sufficiently to turn into a liquid.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When the gas is compressed, the molecules are brought closer together, making it easier to condense.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Lowering the temperature reduces the kinetic energy of the gas molecules, further aiding in the transition from gas to liquid.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This principle is used in various industrial processes, including the production of liquefied natural gas (LNG).&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Critical Temperature and Pressure&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;critical temperature&lt;/strong&gt; is the highest temperature at which a substance can exist as a liquid. Above this temperature, a gas cannot be liquefied, regardless of pressure.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;critical pressure&lt;/strong&gt; is the pressure required to liquefy a gas at its critical temperature.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Boyle&amp;rsquo;s Law and Charles&amp;rsquo;s Law&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Boyle&amp;rsquo;s Law&lt;/strong&gt; states that the pressure of a given mass of gas is inversely proportional to its volume at a constant temperature.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Charles&amp;rsquo;s Law&lt;/strong&gt; states that the volume of a gas is directly proportional to its temperature at constant pressure.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Industrial Applications&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Liquefaction is used in the storage and transport of gases such as oxygen, nitrogen, and natural gas.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Liquefied gases are easier to store and transport as they take up less space.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Refrigeration Cycles&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The principles of gas liquefaction are applied in refrigeration cycles, where refrigerants are compressed and expanded to absorb and release heat.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This process is used in air conditioning systems and refrigerators.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;option 1&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The gravitational force between two objects is directly proportional to the product of their masses.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is inversely proportional to the square of the distance between the two objects.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This relationship is defined by Newton&amp;#39;s law of universal gravitation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Newton&amp;#39;s law states that every point mass attracts every other point mass by a force acting along the line intersecting both points.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Newton&amp;#39;s Law of Universal Gravitation:&lt;/strong&gt; This law states that every mass attracts every other mass in the universe with a force that is directly proportional to the product of their masses and inversely proportional to the square of the distance between their centers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Gravitational Constant (G):&lt;/strong&gt; The proportionality constant in Newton&amp;#39;s law of gravitation is known as the gravitational constant, which has a value of approximately 6.674 &amp;times; 10&lt;sup&gt;-11&lt;/sup&gt; N(m/kg)&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Inverse-square Law:&lt;/strong&gt; The inverse-square law indicates that a specified physical quantity is inversely proportional to the square of the distance from the source of that physical quantity.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Applications:&lt;/strong&gt; Newton&amp;#39;s law of gravitation applies to a wide range of physical phenomena, from the orbits of planets and moons to the trajectories of satellites and the motion of objects on Earth.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Bryophyllum - Spore formation&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Bryophyllum&lt;/strong&gt; reproduces vegetatively through leaf buds, not through spore formation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Vegetative reproduction&lt;/strong&gt; in Bryophyllum occurs when plantlets arise from the notches at the margins of its leaves.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Each plantlet can develop into a new individual when it falls onto the soil, a process known as &lt;strong&gt;propagation by fragmentation&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In contrast, &lt;strong&gt;spore formation&lt;/strong&gt; is a mode of asexual reproduction seen in fungi, algae, and some non-flowering plants, but not in Bryophyllum.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Binary Fission in Amoeba&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Amoeba reproduces asexually by binary fission, where the cell divides into two equal parts.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This process involves the replication of the genetic material followed by the division of the cytoplasm.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Budding in Hydra&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Hydra reproduces by budding, a form of asexual reproduction where a new organism develops from an outgrowth or bud on the parent.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The bud detaches when it is mature enough to survive on its own.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Fragmentation in Spirogyra&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Spirogyra, a filamentous green alga, reproduces through fragmentation where a filament breaks into smaller pieces, each of which can grow into a new individual.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This method is common in simple multicellular organisms and some plants.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;law of inertia&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The first law of motion is also known as the &lt;strong&gt;law of inertia&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It states that an object will remain at rest or in uniform motion in a straight line unless acted upon by an external force.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This law was formulated by Sir Isaac Newton and is one of the fundamental principles of classical mechanics.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The law of inertia explains the behavior of objects in the absence of external forces.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Linear Momentum:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Linear momentum is the product of the mass and velocity of an object.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is a vector quantity, having both magnitude and direction.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Conservation of linear momentum is a fundamental principle in physics.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Torque:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Torque is a measure of the force that can cause an object to rotate about an axis.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is calculated as the product of force and the distance from the point of rotation.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is also a vector quantity.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Angular Momentum:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Angular momentum is the rotational equivalent of linear momentum.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It depends on the object&amp;#39;s moment of inertia and its angular velocity.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Like linear momentum, angular momentum is also conserved in a closed system.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Newton&amp;#39;s Laws of Motion:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Newton&amp;#39;s first law is the law of inertia.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Newton&amp;#39;s second law states that force is equal to mass times acceleration (F=ma).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Newton&amp;#39;s third law states that for every action, there is an equal and opposite reaction.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 2: The object moves with a constant speed.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;An object in uniform motion travels equal distances in equal intervals of time, indicating a constant speed.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Uniform motion implies that the velocity of the object does not change over time.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In uniform motion, both the magnitude and direction of the object&amp;#39;s velocity remain constant.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The path of an object in uniform motion can be linear or circular, but the speed remains constant throughout the motion.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Velocity:&lt;/strong&gt; It is the speed of an object in a given direction. Uniform motion implies constant velocity.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Acceleration:&lt;/strong&gt; The rate of change of velocity. In uniform motion, the acceleration is zero since the velocity is constant.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Displacement:&lt;/strong&gt; The change in position of an object. In uniform motion, displacement is directly proportional to time.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Graphical Representation:&lt;/strong&gt; A distance-time graph of an object in uniform motion is a straight line, indicating constant speed.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Non-Uniform Motion:&lt;/strong&gt; When an object travels unequal distances in equal intervals of time, the motion is termed non-uniform, indicating varying speed.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;the dividing tissue, also known as meristematic tissue, is located only at these regions&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Meristematic tissue&lt;/strong&gt; is composed of cells that have the ability to divide and form new cells, which is essential for plant growth.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These tissues are found in specific regions such as the tips of roots and shoots, and in the cambium layer of stems.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Meristematic cells are undifferentiated and retain the ability to undergo mitosis continuously.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The growth in length (primary growth) and thickness (secondary growth) of plants is attributed to the activity of meristematic tissue.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Examples of meristematic tissues include apical meristems, intercalary meristems, and lateral meristems.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Apical Meristems:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Located at the tips of roots and shoots.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Responsible for primary growth in plants, resulting in an increase in length.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Intercalary Meristems:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Found at the base of leaves or internodes (stem regions between the places where leaves attach).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Facilitate regrowth of grasses and other monocots after cutting or grazing.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Lateral Meristems:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Located along the sides of stems and roots.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Responsible for secondary growth, which increases the girth of the plant.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Examples include the vascular cambium and cork cambium.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Permanent Tissue:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Consists of differentiated cells that have lost the ability to divide.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Includes tissues such as xylem, phloem, and epidermis.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Plant Growth:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Involves both cell division and cell enlargement.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Regulated by plant hormones such as auxins, gibberellins, and cytokinins.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Newton&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The SI unit of force is called the &lt;strong&gt;Newton&lt;/strong&gt;, symbolized as &amp;quot;N&amp;quot;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;One Newton is defined as the amount of force required to accelerate a &lt;strong&gt;1 kilogram mass by 1 meter per second squared&lt;/strong&gt; (1 N = 1 kg&amp;middot;m/s&amp;sup2;).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Newton is named after Sir &lt;strong&gt;Isaac Newton&lt;/strong&gt; in recognition of his work in classical mechanics, particularly Newton&amp;#39;s Laws of Motion.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The unit was adopted in the International System of Units (SI) in &lt;strong&gt;1948&lt;/strong&gt; during the 9th General Conference on Weights and Measures (CGPM).&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dyne&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A dyne is a unit of force in the centimeter-gram-second (CGS) system of units.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is equal to 10^-5 Newtons (1 dyne = 10^-5 N).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Newton&amp;#39;s Laws of Motion&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;There are three fundamental laws that describe the relationship between the motion of an object and the forces acting on it.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These laws form the foundation of classical mechanics.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Force&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;In physics, force is an interaction that, when unopposed, will change the motion of an object.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It can be described as a push or pull on an object resulting from the object&amp;#39;s interaction with another object.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;SI Units&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The International System of Units (SI) is the modern form of the metric system.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is the most widely used system of measurement, established in 1960.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;It is normal to the mirror at its pole.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The principal axis of a spherical mirror is a straight line that passes through the center of curvature and the pole of the mirror.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is normal (perpendicular) to the surface of the mirror at the pole (the geometric center of the mirror&amp;#39;s surface).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The principal axis is used as a reference line for drawing ray diagrams and for defining various points related to the mirror, such as the focal point and the center of curvature.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The principal axis helps in understanding the image formation by concave and convex mirrors.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Pole (P)&lt;/strong&gt;: The pole is the midpoint of the spherical mirror&amp;#39;s surface. It is the point where the principal axis meets the mirror.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Center of Curvature (C)&lt;/strong&gt;: The center of curvature is the center of the sphere from which the spherical mirror is a part. It lies on the principal axis.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Radius of Curvature (R)&lt;/strong&gt;: The radius of curvature is the distance between the pole and the center of curvature. It is equal to the radius of the sphere from which the mirror is made.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Focal Point (F)&lt;/strong&gt;: The focal point is the point on the principal axis where parallel rays of light either converge (concave mirror) or appear to diverge (convex mirror) after reflection. It is located at half the distance between the pole and the center of curvature.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Focal Length (f)&lt;/strong&gt;: The focal length is the distance between the pole and the focal point. It is given by the formula f = R/2, where R is the radius of curvature.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;an oxidising agent&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Bleaching powder (Calcium hypochlorite) is a strong oxidising agent, which means it can donate oxygen to other substances and oxidize them.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is commonly used in chemical industries for bleaching paper pulp, textiles, and disinfecting drinking water due to its ability to kill bacteria and other pathogens.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Bleaching powder releases chlorine when exposed to air and moisture, which contributes to its oxidising properties.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is widely used in the textile industry to bleach cotton and linen and in the paper industry to bleach wood pulp.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Oxidising Agents&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Oxidising agents are substances that can accept electrons and bring about oxidation of other substances.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Common oxidising agents include substances like hydrogen peroxide, potassium permanganate, and chlorine.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They are used in various industrial processes including disinfection, bleaching, and water treatment.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Calcium Hypochlorite&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Calcium hypochlorite, commonly known as bleaching powder, is a white solid, often used for water treatment and as a bleaching agent.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Its chemical formula is Ca(ClO)&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is more stable than sodium hypochlorite (liquid bleach) and has a longer shelf life.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Disinfection Process&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Disinfection involves the elimination of most or all pathogenic microorganisms, except bacterial spores, from inanimate objects.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Bleaching powder is used to disinfect drinking water and swimming pools by killing harmful microorganisms.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Safety Measures&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;When handling bleaching powder, it is important to use protective gear, such as gloves and masks, to avoid irritation and inhalation of fumes.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It should be stored in a dry, cool place away from organic materials and acids to prevent hazardous reactions.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Chromosomes&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Chromosomes are rod-shaped structures that become visible during cell division.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are composed of DNA and proteins and carry genetic information.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Chromosomes ensure that DNA is accurately replicated and distributed during cell division.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Each species has a characteristic number of chromosomes; for humans, it&amp;#39;s 46.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Chromatin:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Chromatin is a complex of DNA and protein found in the nucleus, which condenses to form chromosomes during cell division.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;In its uncondensed form, chromatin is involved in gene expression and DNA replication.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mitosis:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Mitosis is the process of cell division that results in two daughter cells with the same number of chromosomes as the parent cell.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It involves stages such as prophase, metaphase, anaphase, and telophase.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Meiosis:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Meiosis is a type of cell division that reduces the chromosome number by half, resulting in four daughter cells, each with half the number of chromosomes of the parent cell.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is essential for sexual reproduction and genetic diversity.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Genome:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The genome is the complete set of genes or genetic material present in a cell or organism.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;In humans, the genome is organized into 23 pairs of chromosomes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
